ownedComment.body: This is the data model for describing simulations, the code that produced them and other related resources. It is to be used by protocol specifications for discovering theory data products and web services with which these can be accessed. An example of these are the Simulation Database (SimDB) spec and the family of protocols to be defined in the Simulation Data Access Layer (SimDAL). This data model is a specification of the IVOA Theory Interest Group.
This profile defines the domain specific UML dialect for the IVOA data modelling efforts.

This package stores predefined data types for use in defining attributes of types in the data model. These types are generic and does not represent specific implementation types. Hence for example we do not make a distinction between 2,4,8 byte integers or floats. The numerical types instead correspond to the commonly used number fields: N,Z,Q,R,C. Most types are primitive, i.e. they represent a single value and have no structure.

A string, represented as an array of characters treated as a single, primitive value. Ala Java, a string can not be updated, that is any update leads to a different string. However in contrast to Java we assume that two strings that are identifcal in all their constitutent characters are the same.
Represents a moment in time using a date+timestamp. Coordinate reference systems must be defined by the context serialisation.

Represents an interval of time from beginning to end. Is not equivalent to s simple real value indicating the number of seconds (for example). In general a custom mapping to a particular serialisation context must be provided.
The standard boolean, having values true or false.
Represents a URI in the same way as the datatype of the same nam in XML Schema is used.
An integer number (from Z).
A rational number from Q, represented by two integers, a numerator and a denominator. A native mapping to a serialisation context does in general not exists.
A real number (from R).

Represents a complex number, consisting of a real and imaginary component, oth of which are reals. Note that in many contexts there is no native mapping for this type and it must be treated with a custom mapping.
An integer number from N, therefore greater than or equal to 0.
Represents a decimal number with exact significand such as used to denote monetary values.
This datatype represents an identifier for an object in the data model. It consists of 3 attributes that each are assumed to work in a particular context or representation of a data model instance.
The id attribute is assumed to represent an object in a database storing instances of the data model.
This attribute is used to support identifing of and referring to an object in an XML document using the ID/IDREF mechanism.

The ivoId attribute is assumed to represent an object in a database following the design of the data model and accessible through a standardised registration and discovery protocols. It is assumed to be unique within the IVOA and its format follows (a generalisation of) the IVO Resource Identifier standard (see http://www.ivoa.net/Documents/REC/Identifiers/Identifiers-20070302.html). Since the ivoId is assumed to represent the resource as registered in a standard database for the data model, it is assumed to be allocated by such a database service. This is in contrast to the use of the IVO Identifier in resource registries, where the id is assumed to be allocated by the publisher. We have the publisherDID attribute for that purpose. Also in contrast to that usage is the fact that each object in the model is assigned this identifier, not only the root resources. We suggest as algorithm for assigning these ivoId to use as root the ivoId of the registered database service, and to append to this a # then the UTYPE of the element and finally its id attribute, separetd from the UTYPE by a forward slash.

This attribute identifies an element in the context of the publisher. It is supposed to be unique in the IVO context and should likely be constrained to have the publisher's authority IVO id. This may need to be rediscussed when protocols for accessing a database built around a data model are to be designed.

specification.body: Only one end which points to the referenced objecttype is navigable.
Only the referencedEnd has a name.

ownedComment.body: This stereotype indicates that a particular Binary Association End has composition semantics. This is assumed by default for such assiciation ends that are navigable and are not shared. However assigning this stereotype allows one to add some attributes to the relation using tags. To this end the stereotype has tag definitions.

specification.body: Only the composed objects end is navigable.
The composied objects end has aggregationKind = "none"
Only the composed objects end has a name.
Usage dependency exists only from one package to another package.
Between two different entity containment trees no cyclic reference is allowed.
A base objectytpe is always abstract.or a concrete objecttype is final

ownedComment.body: This stereotype indicates that an atribute represents a term in a particular SKOS vocabulary. This stereotype indicates that a particular Binary Association End has composition semantics. Assigning this stereotype allows one to add some attributes to the relation using tags. To this end the stereotype has tag definitions, in particular the vocabularyURI indicating which particular vocabulary the concept should be extracted from.

This sterotype indicates that a given Property has attribute semantics. This is by default the case for our attributes that must have a datatype cosen form the IVOAValueTypes, howevere the explicit assignment of this stereotype allows the modeller to assign specific extra attributes as tags. For that purpose this stereotype has various tag definitions.

MaxLength defines the maximum length for a string value (or the precision for a number).
If MaxLength is undefined, then the following rules apply : - String [30] - Number [Real 4 bytes] for floating point numbers - Number [Integer 4 bytes] for integer numbers
This guarantees that that value is unique in a collection so a couple (container_id, attribute) must be unique
This attribute must be unique in the SimDB Database (unique contraints)
Indicates that this field can be used to order a collection of parent class
Any model element can be given this sterotype. It allows one to add some specific labels as tags to the element. For example UTYPE.

If the model element represents an element in another data model, that element can be indicated by adding its UTYPE as this tag's value. Note that we allow an element to have multiple UTYPEs (multiplicity = 0..*).

This is the root package of the SimDB data model. It contains the other packages of the model as subpackages. It contains the Resource and Party root entity classes and various data types and enumerations.
This package contains the SimDB Experiment class, its subclasses and and other types contained by these. It is a sub-package of the simdb package.

This class represents the execution of simulation codes. Its protocol is therefore a Simulator iso a general Protocol. It extends Experiment by adding descriptions of the physical processes that were simulated

Reference to the Simulator that was used to run this Simulation. Thie reference overrrides(subsets) the simlar reference from Experiment to Protocol, indicating that the type of the protocol reference must be a Simulator, not just any Protocol.
The date/time at which the simulation was completed

This collections associates this Simulation to the Simulator's physics that was actually used. This element represents the possibility in most simulator codes to turn on or off specific physical processes in a simulation run. Examples are the option to have a pure dark matter simulation in an SPH code. Or a hydro code without gravity. The collection of AppliedPhysics objects references thos modules that were actually used.
The simulator that was used in this simulation. This reference overrides the protocol reference of Experiment, indicating that not any protocol can be added as a reference, but only a Simulator

This class represents the characterisation of a property of an object in a given object collection. It represents both a priori and a posteriori characterisations. With a priori characterisation we indicate possible and/or nominal [?] values the variable may take, it defines the possible range of values of the property. In contrast, an a posteriori characterisation of a property in an object collection provides summarising, likely statistical, information on the values that were actually taken up (observed, simulated) by the objects in the collection. The a priori characterisation is most similar, in fact a generalisation of the Characterisation model of the IVOA Data Model working group [3].
In the current model we stick to simple (numerical) quantities for characterising a collection of objects. For example the equivalent value of a support from [3] is absent, as it is not terribly useful for discovery and querying, even more so of course for concepts equivalent to sensitivity. [TBD How relevant is it for simulations? Examples if we require it for the actual meta data specification, for example for usages beyond query and discovery.]
TODO currently the characterisation is restricted to numericalobservables, generalisation comes later.
This attribute indicates which statistic is used to characterise the referenced object property.
Summarising value of a numerical property in a collection of objects

If 'true', this attribute indicates that the characterisation is aPriori. That is it indicates that the value says something about what the publisher believes are the possible values the characterised property can assume. An "p priori" characterisation is therefore a summary of the effects that the input configuration (parameters, input data, the "provenance-actual experiment" therefore) is EXPECTED to have on the final result (represented by the collections of representation objects and their properties).
Alternatively, if the value is "false", it indicates that the charecterisation is a posteriori, i.e. it says something about the actual values that were assumed. This requires in general some level of post processing beyond simply storing the result, but as in general the characterisation types are simple statistical quantities this need not modelled as a separate experiment.

The property of the object type that is being characterised. In the IVOA DM's characterisation model this is represented by specified objects, such as spatialaxis, timeaxis etc. Here we do not know in advance which kind of property is characterised, hence this explicit reference.
In case a string-typed property is summarised here this attribute should be used to give the value.

This class represents a single consistent data product that is produced by an experiment. A Product can consist of a single or multiple files, or possibly one or more tables in a database, or subsets thereof. The exact storage is not currently modelled. A Product is a collection of objects representing the same ObjectType. A Result is built from a collection of one or more products that together represent a particular Target. For example, a simulato such as Gadget2 can produce both dark matter, stellar and gas particles, together building up one or more target objects. Each of these sets of particles is in general separately characterised and the Product class provides an anchor for this. The product class can also be labelled with a common name, the productType.
This collection contains the characterisations of the different properties that summarise the properties of the representation objects in this object collection.
Gives the number of objects in this collection
This reference indicates the type of object stored in this collection.
Indicates the type of product as a concept in a SKOS vocabulary of ProductTypes.

Represents an optional reference to a URL from which the product can be obtained. No statement is made on whether this should represent a simple file for download, or a link to a web page with information how to obtain it.
See also the description of the InputData class for a discussion about storage of products.

the characterisations of the different variables. In contrast to the domain model in [2] we make no distinction w.r.t. a priori and a posteriori characterisation as separate classes/collection, but load all possible characterising quantities in one

The SimDB Experiment represents the execution of a computer program represented by a SimDB Protocol. It defines how the program was run by providing values to parameters for example. It describes the goal of the experiment in terms of the physical objects and processes that are being simulated and it contains the collection of results.
Reference to the Protocol used in the exeuciton of this Experiment. Subclasses of this Experiment will in general override/"subset" this reference to subclasses of Protocol.
The collection of ParameterSetting objects that describe the values assigned to parameters of the Protocol used in the execution of this Experiment.
The collection of InputData objects, indicating results of other Esperiments that may have been used in the execution of this Experiment.
The collection of ExperimentRepresentationObject objects that indicate which of the available RepresentationObjectTypes on a Protocl were actually produced in the execution of the experiment.
Collection of AppliedAlgorithm objects, indicating which Algorithms available on a Protocl were used in the execution of the Experiment.
This collection of Target, describing the different targets/goals/objectives of this Experiment.
The collection of Results that were produced in the execution of this Experiment.

This class represents a part of the universe at a particular point in time, or possibly a more general sub-volume of space-time, for example a light-cone. It is a special type of simdb/experiment/Result and introduced to faciltate queries on simulations producing 3+1D results, the goal of the original SNAP project. As defined, a Snapshot does not represent all possible outputs of such 3+1D simulations. For example some simulations of dense (collisional) stellar systems produce orbits of the individual particles, at individual output times . In general those results can be and are used to produce snapshots as well (Peter Teuben, private communication).

The time in the simulation at which this snapshot is produced. A real value in terms of the timestep units that are being used. [TBD need to find a place for those units, note that we need to support co-moving quantities !]

The typical size of the target system in this snapshot. Left up to the data publisher to give a useful value for this. Is not necessarily equal to the size of the box containing the full simulation (covered by Characterisation). Could be the rough size of the galaxy merger, or cluster, or the size of a box containing 90% of the mass or whatever
Represents an experiment that corresponds to the execution of a PostProcessor protocol. It manipulates a pre-existing result to produce new results, but without introducing new physics.

The experiment whose results are being post-processed by this PostProcessing step.
TBD This is a very simple(simplistic) view of post-processing, that the results of a single experiment are manipulated only.
The post-processing protocol according to which the post-processing experiment is performed. Overrides the protocol reference on Experiment.

Many experiments require pre-existing data products for their running. This class represents such an association for its parent Experiment. We assume that we can represent the input data by a Product.
TBD This requires that the input data is represented in the model by the experiment that created it. Whereas that would be optimal, it may not always be practical. We may want to consider implementing the reference instead by an accessURL attribute on this class. This would allow a user to find out whether a product exists in the database with that same url, make the link indirect but arguably more correct. In the "Domain Model" this accessURL was represented by a separate PhysicalArtefact class.
Describes the role that the input data set plays in the experiment.
The product that is used as input data for an Experiment.
BLA Reference to the Protocol used in the exeuciton of this Experiment. Subclasses of this Experiment will in general override/"subset" this reference to subclasses of Protocol.
The properties of the object. Ex: mass, position,velocity

This class represents the fact that some simulations are run with the goal (Target) to investigate physical processes, rather than simulation specific objects or systems. Instances of this class can be used to describe this. For example one may study "turbulence", or "gravitational cluster" or "galaxy formation".
A term from the AstroJournalSubjectKeywords ontology.

To run an Experiment, one usually needs to assign values to parameters defined on the corresponding Protocol. This class makes the association between the Experiment and the parameters, indicating which parameter is given what value.
Input parameters can be given any datatype from the DataType enumeration and hence it is in principle impossible to assign a single datatype to the value attribute storing the parameter setting in this model. Whereas we might use a generic string data type, this will in many implementations limit the use of query expressions that one might use for numerical values for example.
As a work around the current design has two attributes, one of type real, one of type string. The former should be used for numerical InputParanmeters, the latter for all others.
Reference to the actual input parameter whose value is being set.
Attribute that holds on to the actual parameter value in case the referenced input parameter is not a numerical type.
Attribute that holds on to the actual parameter value in case the referenced input parameter is a numerical type.

The collection of simulator input parameters used in this simulation. These parameters must correspond to actual parameters that can be set on the simulator.
the parameters used in the experiment. In this logical model the parameters are both defined and given a value in a single object. In the analysis model parameters are defined on the protocol, and only given a value on the experiment

The AppliedPhysics class represents the association between a physical process on a Simulator and this class' parent Simulation. Many simulation codes allow one to turn on or off modules corresponding to different physics. For example certain SPH codes allow one to turn off the hydrodynamics, leaving only gravity as the physical process being simulated.
Reference to the Simulator's Physcis module that is used in the Simulation.
The collection of physical processes modelled in this simulation

This enumeration lists possible statistics that can be used to characterise a collection of Property-s in a result. The literals in this enumeration in general correspond to the result of simple statistical operation on this collection (when a posteriori) or on the corresponding operation on the a priori probability distribtion (assuming this can be defined) of its values.
There is overlap between this enumeration and the 'stat' family of UCDs in the UCD controlled vocabulary (http://www.ivoa.net/Documents/REC/UCD/UCDlist-20070402.html). Where this enumeration is used one might consider using a vocabulary based on those terms.
In case a product contains exactly 1 object, the value statistic should be used to indicate the actual property value.
A typical value, as judged by the publisher of the snapshots. May not correspond to a predefined statistical operation such as mean or mode.
Represents the minimum ('possible' if a priori, 'attained' if a osteriori) value for the characterised property.
Represents the maximum ('possible' if a priori, 'attained' if a osteriori) value for the characterised property.
Represents the mode of the distribution ('expected' if a priori, 'attained' if a posteriori) for the characterised property.
Represents the mean ('expected' if a priori, 'attained' if a posteriori) value for the characterised property.
Represents the median of a distribution.
Represents the expected/attained standard deviation for the characterised property.
Represents the expected/attained variance for the characterised property.

Protocols often allow one to choose which representation object types one wants to use in an experiment. For example, SPH codes may have dark matter particles, gass particles, star particles. A given experiment may not require all. This class associates the experiment to the actual representation object types that are used.
Reference to the RepresentationObjectType that is associated to the experiment by this association class.

Apart form allowing a user the freedom to choose between available representation object types, Protocols may also allow one to choose from available properties on the selected object.This collection embodies that choice for the selected experiment representation object.
Indicates the different object types used to represent the system that is being simulated/produced by the experiment
the type of used object

Apart form allowing a user the freedom to choose between available representation object types, Protocols may also allow one to choose from available properties on the selected object. This class represents such a choice.
Reference to the property that is being chosen by the ExperimentProperty object.

This class represents the actual system that is being simulated. Instances of this object should correspond to physical objects and/or systems. They should be the answer to queries such as, “what does this simulation simulate?”
Indication on how many objects of this type are being modelled. [TBD This may become an enumerated value, like “one, two, tens, many ...”].

If the target object type referes to a real object, this attribute allows one to indicate which object. This is performed by a URI that shold identify the object in the Ontology of SimbadIdentifiedNames
In some cases a real identified object in the universe is being modelled. If that is the case, this attribute allows that object to be identified. We assume a list of such objects may be provided through some means, embodied by the IdentifiedObject data type. Ex: Galaxy, Antennae, M31
TBD can this be seen as a SKOS concept ?
Represents a concept in a SKOS vocabulary of astronomical and astrophysical object types.

The property of the object type that is being characterised. In the IVOA DM's characterisation model this is represented by specified objects, such as spatialaxis, timeaxis etc. Here we do not know in advance which kind of property is characterised, hence this explicit reference.

indication how this physical process is implemented in the simulator. If there is in general only one Algorithm required per Physics oject, we may consider putting the Algorithm.label attribute as an attribute on the Physics class and remove the Algorithm class. Ex: (gravity) tree-PM, (hydrodynamics) AMR

The AppliedAlgorithm class represents the application of a particular algorithm in an experiment. Some simulation codes allow one to choose between different algorithms for representing a particular process. For example some N-Body codes allow one to choose between Tree-only or Tree+ParticleMesh codes. To indicate which algorithms were actually used in an experiment one adds an instance of this AppliedAlgorithm class to the collection on the experiment.
Reference to the actual algorithm that is applied

This class represents a result of an experiment. This can be a snapshot of an N-Body simulation, or a halo catalogue of a cluster finder. SimDB follows the "Domain Model for Astronomy" in defining a result as one or more products, which are collections of "atomic" objects, such as N-Body particles, or mesh cells, but represents these by characterising statistics only.
A Result is supposed to be a result for one of the Targets of the experiment. This is actually the main classifying principle to define a new result, namely whether it represents one or another of the target objects.

The collection of Products owned by an experimental result. We anticipate that many results contain objects of different ObjectType-s. For each of these types a separate collection of objects, a product, is provided on the result.

This reference indicates to which Experiment.target a result applies. The target must have the same parent Experiment as the referencing Result.
TBD 2010-05-24 We need to discuss whether assigning a target to a result using a 0..1 reference is not too restricted for the purposes of the data model. In general data products may contain information about mutiple targets, and the same target may be represented by/in multiple data prducts and results.
A short description of the Result.
We anticipate that many results contain objects of different types. For each of these types a separate collection of objects, a product, is provided on the result.

This class represents a genetic result. It is a concrete representation of a result that is not a snapshot. It is introduced to satisfy the modelling principle that base classes (i.e. classes that have a subclass), must be abstract.

Represents the scientific goal of a simulation. Is made concrete by suclasses representing objects or processes. We model a Target as "being an" ObjectType, which allows one to give a more detailed representation of its properties. The target is important as it allows one to classify the different results. Each result must have a reference to the target it represents through its various products.
This package contains the SimDB Protocol and classes used in its definition.

This class represents a physical processes that is modelled in a simulation code. Simulating a physical process generally corresponds to solving equations of motion numerically, evolving the simulated system from one state to the next.
Name by which this physical process is represented in the simulator code
Short description of the physical process represented by this class.

The name by which this process is (approximately) known in the IVOA ontology of physical processes. For example: gravity, hydrodynamics, cosmology.
The name by which this process is (approximately) known in the list of subject keywords of the Astrophysical Journal, MNRAS and A&A.
TBD This description must be adjusted to the actual SKOS vocabulary that is assigned to this label.

This class represents the simulation software that is available to run a simulation. It is different from other SimDB Protocols in that it explicitly indicates the physical processes that can be simulated. Tghis indeed can be seen as a defining characteristic of a Simulator: it models physical processes. This in contrast to a "mere" post-processor which takes the input data and analyses it without adding new physics. It does not imply that simulators can not use existing results. For example consider semi-analytical galaxy formation routines which work on existing halo (merger) catalogues.
Collection of physical processes that can be simulated using this simulator.

A SimDB Protocol represents a software code that can be used to run simulations or to post-process simulation results. A Protocol defines how SimDB experiments can be performed, like a blue-print, or template. The protocol concept is separated out from the execution of its code in Experiment, which allows us to reuse it for all experiments using the same code.
TBD Is the name confusing wrt to the "standard protocols" such as defined by the DAL WG? Should we name it SoftwareProtocol for example?
link where the code can be downloaded, if available
the version of the simulator code that was used
Collection of parameter groups. This is a utility colection, indicating that a particular grouping of parameters is natural. Useful for browsing the protocol's contents.
The collection of representation objects available to represent the 3+1D universe in this protocol.
Collection of input parameters for this protocol.

This collection indicates which algorithms were applied in the experiment.
TODO should be put on Protocol with an association object taking its place under Experiment

This concrete subclass of Protocol represents protocols that deal with post-processing results of earlier experiments. We do not specify the details of this type much further. Main difference with eg the Simulator type is that NO physicaal processes are introduced. Examples are cluster finders, visualisers etc. In the current modle it IS assumed that Postprocessor produce Snapshots, i.e. representations of 3+1D space-time. This may need to be generalised if we want to allow for example also a power-spectrum or correlation function calculator as part of a SimDB.

Represents a (natural) grouping of input parameters. Especially in protocols with large numbers of parameters it may be useful to group these for browsing purposes for example. As browsing is likely an important mode of access to SimDB resources this possibility was introduced.
Short description of the purpose of this group.
Name given to this group.
Collection of associative member objects, indicating which parameter is part of the group.

Represents a concept in a SKOS vocabulary suitable for for parameter groups. Parameter groups may be useful to define especially (if not only) when they represent a well defined concept. This label allows one to define that concept
Associative class, representing a selection of a parameter in a parameter grouping.
Reference to the selected input parameter.

This class represents the smallest units from which a target system/object is built. It defines also the actual objects that the Snapshot-s contain. Examples are the particles in an N-body simulation, the cells in an adaptive mesh simulations, the halos in the result of a group finder

Indicates the type of representation object according to the enumeration defined in this model.
TODO we need to decide whether we need this label to be an ontology term instead of getting values form an enumeraiton.
Name that this type of particle is given in an appropriate SKOS vocabulary.

Represents a standard name for the objects that can be used to represent a snapshot of the universe in SimDB data products. Examples from simulations are “n-body particle”, “SPH particle”, “mesh cell”. But also simplified representations of astronomical objects could be used here, for example in halo catalogues or semi-analytical galaxy catalogues, both results of post-processing experiments
NB This should be transferred to an appropriate external ontology!
Represents the case where point particles are used to represent the simulated world.
Represents the case where extended particles with hydro properties are used to represent the simulated world in an SPH simulation.
Represents the case whereextended particles are used to represent the simulated world.
Represents the case where simple, non-structured/subdivided mesh cells are used to represent the simulated world in a regular grid.
Represents the case where mesh cells taht may be hierarchically subdivided are used to represent the simulated world in an adaptive mesh refinemenet simulation.

Represents the case where mock astronomical objects with their "physical" properties are used to represent the simulated world. Mainly found in results of post-processing. Examples are dark matter halos as the result of a cluster finder, synthetic galaxies as the result of semi-analytical simulations or halo occupation distributions algorithms.
Represents the case wherecustom objects, for which there is no existing term available in this enumeration, are used to represent the simulated world.

This class represent an input parameter on a protocol. In general,a simulation codes needs the user to set values to parameters that govern the running of the code. These may be parameters describing the physics in a simulation, or they may be numerical parameters governing the approximation of the process by a particular algorithm.

A label to be given to this input parameter from an appropriate SKOS vocabulary.
TBD For now we assume the existence of a SKOS concept "inputParameter" in a similar vocabulary. This description should be adjusted once the actual vocabulary is decided.

This class represents numerical algorithms available in a SimDB Protocol. In Simulators an algorithm may approximate a physical process. Examples from cosmological simulations are different algorithms to implement gravity: direct particle-particle interaction, particle-mesh, or various types of tree based algorithms. In post-processors such as cluster finder this class can represent a partiular cluster definition such as friends-of-friends or spherical overdensity.
A common name given to this algorithm.
Short description of this algorithm.

Short name by which this implementation is known in the SKOS vocabulary of numerical algorithms in http://vocabularies.referata.com/wiki/Category:VOT_Algorithm. For example: n-body, tree, amr, sphe, ...
TBD the SKOS vocabulary must be completed and these examples should be updated accordingly.

This class represents a resource in SimDB in the same way as the Registry Resource class does in that model. These are the root entities that get registered in a SimDB instance.
This class is a thin copy of the Registry Resource and borrows some of its elements. It *is not* a Registry Resource in the sense of inheritance. In particular a SimDB Resource has a more refined and targeted content model. Also, SimDB Resource-s are in general (much) more fine grained than Registry Resource-s and would not qualify to be registered in a Registry. It may be possible to tarnsform certain SimDb Resource-s into Registry Resource-s.

For Protocol : The name by which this simulator is commonly known. Ex: Gadget, Flash
For Project : the name of the project
For Experiment : the name of this experiment
A description of this resource.
a URL to a web page describing the resource.
The UTC date and time this resource was created in the real world.
The UTC date this resource metadata description was last updated.
a tag indicating whether this resource is believed to be still actively maintained.
The collection of contacts for a Reource.
Information that describes a Party, that is a person/individual or possibly an organisation.

the name or title of the contact person.
This can be a person's name, e.g. "John P. Jones" or a group, "Archive Support Team".
the contact email address

the contact mailing address
All components of the mailing address are given in one string, e.g. "3700 San Martin Drive, Baltimore, MD 21218 USA".

the contact telephone number
Complete international dialing codes should be given, e.g. "+1-410-338-1234".

The DataType enumeration lists the available values for the datatype attributes used in the definition of metadata fields such as Property and InputParameter. The values represent rather abstract data types. For example no distinction is made between different representations of integer (short, int, long) or floating point (float, double) types. Instead the mathematical number fields integer and real are used, together with rational and complex. Alternative representations or usages of this model might add such details.
A standard boolean type, with values 'true' and 'false', possibly represented differently in physical representations of the model.

A standard complex type. Here no limits on accuracy of constituent Re and Im parts is made, they are assumed to be real. TODO find a proper representation of this datatype in the various serialisations: XSD, DDL, Java.
Represents an exact time on an exact, given date. No accuracy is assumed.
A floating point datatype, without impied accuracy.
An integer datatype, without implied accuracy.
A rational datatype, consisting of two integers representing the numerator and denominator. TODO find a proper serialisation to derived representations: XSD, DDL, Java.
A standard string datatype consisting of any type of character.
This enumeration contains the possible values for the cardinality attribute of a Field definition.
Corresponds to 'Optional element'
Corresponds to 'Mandatory element'
Corresponds to 'Multiple but maybe Optional element'
Corresponds to 'Multiple with at least one element'
A structured data type, indicating a numerical value and corresponding unit. The latter will require some standard dictionary for a uniform usage. This is here not modelled
The numerical value for this quantity.
The unit (if applicable) for this quantity. Should correspond to a recognised unit, possibly a skosconcept?
This package contains SimDB ObjectType and classes used in its definition. These classes allow users to describe structured objects that are used in the simulations and other codes.
This class assists in the definition of an object hierarchy by associating a child to a parent object.
Reference to the ObjectType that is the child in the hierarchical parent-child relation.
Name of the variable representing the child object on the parent object.
The cardinality/multiplicity of the child object in the containing object.
Describes the relation between the parent and child object type.
Assocuiative object that represents a member in a property group.
Reference to the actual property this class associates to a property group.
This class represents a naturla grouping of properties on the object type. Is used for presentation purposes in a browsing environment.
Name of this paarameter grouping.
Collection of members of this parameter grouping.
Description of this group.

Represents a concept in a SKOS vocabulary suitable for for property groups. Property groups may be useful to define especially (if not only) when they represent a well defined concept. This label allows one to define that concept

This package holds on to SimDB Service and classes used in its definition. It represents functions for accessing the physical resources described by the model such as the results of simulations and post-processing experiments.

This class represents a web service that can be used to access simulation results registered in a SimDB. The precise way in which the web service gives access to these results not specified in detail. It includes simple downloads, and services implementing standards such as SimDAP and possibly S3. SimDB's WebService is related to SimDB Resource and can be used for more general purposes than simply giving access to results of a single experiment. It may be a web service that can handle results of any experiment performed by a particular Protocol, or give access to all resources in a Project.
The main goal of introducing SimDB WebService in the model is so that users can find web services based on requests for specific tyes of simulations etc. For example users may wish to find web services giving access to hydro simulations of clusters of galaxies with particular properties. . It is assumed that web services registerd in a SimDB are also registered in a Registry which will store the more detailed capbilitieis and other service metadata. Therefore such details are not introduced here.

The base URL of this web service. In case the web service implements a standard IVOA protocol such as SimDAP, this base URL can be used in the same way as other typical IVOA S*AP services. Parameters defined by the standard may be added to the base URL so that a proper HTTP GET request can be created for accessing the web service directly.
Collection of resources that are made available in this web service.

The IVO identifier by which this service is registered in an IVOA Resource Registry. Each WebService should be registered in such a registry and this identifier allows one to obtain the full description of this service as defined by the Registry standard.
The AccessibleResource class represents an association between the containing Service and the Resources that are being made accessible by that service.
This reference points to the Resource that the AccessibleResource class associates to the Service. The end point can be any Resource.
Description of how the resource is made available by the parent service.

Direct URI for accessing the referenced resource using the parent service. The parent service has a baseURL through which one goes to the service interface. From there one may be able to browse through all resources that are made available, but a protocol to reach a given resource or how to browse these resources is not defined by this model. IF it is possible to access the resource directly through the service, for example to download or browse its contents, this attribute gives the corresponding URI.
Represents a web service conforming to a SimDAL protocol. This is a place holder until these have been fully specified.

The CustomService class represents a custom web service for accessing SimDB resources. It is not assumed that a predefined protocol is implemented. Its main role is to distinnguish it from SimDAL and other services implementing potential, future IVOA standards.

A SimDB Project is an aggregation of SimDB Resource-s that belong together, for example because they have been produced together in the course of a scientific project. Examples are parameter studies where a large number of simulations is run with slightly varying parameter settings. But also a single large simulation with a number of post-processing results can be gathers in this way.
It is assumed that IF a SimDB Resource can qualify to be turned into a Registry Resources (See the description for Resource), this is first true for a Project.
Collection of associatiions to the resources that make up this project.
Associative class between a Project and its constitutent SimDB/Resource-s.
Reference to another SimDB/Resource that is included in the containing project.
